## Why This Is Asked

This question tests understanding of order statistics in dynamic sets, along with practical implementation details like lazy deletion and handling duplicates.

## Key Concepts

- **Median of a dynamic set**: the middle element (or average of two middle elements) when sorted
- **Two-heap approach**: max-heap for the lower half, min-heap for the upper half
- **Lazy deletion**: defer actual removal until top operations, tracking deletions via a count map
- **Duplicate handling**: maintain frequency counts rather than storing duplicate values multiple times in the heaps

## Code Example

```javascript
class MedianFinder {
  constructor() {
    this.low = new MaxHeap();    // max-heap for lower half
    this.high = new MinHeap();   // min-heap for upper half
    this.delayed = new Map();    // lazy deletion map
  }

  insert(num) {
    if (this.low.isEmpty() || num <= this.low.peek()) {
      this.low.push(num);
    } else {
      this.high.push(num);
    }
    this.rebalance();
  }

  rebalance() {
    if (this.low.size() > this.high.size() + 1) {
      this.high.push(this.low.pop());
    } else if (this.high.size() > this.low.size()) {
      this.low.push(this.high.pop());
    }
  }

  erase(num) {
    this.delayed.set(num, (this.delayed.get(num) || 0) + 1);
    if (num <= this.low.peek()) {
      this.low.deleted++;
    } else {
      this.high.deleted++;
    }
    this.rebalance();
  }

  getMedian() {
    this.prune(this.low);
    this.prune(this.high);
    if (this.low.size() > this.high.size()) {
      return this.low.peek();
    }
    return (this.low.peek() + this.high.peek()) / 2;
  }
}
```

