## Why This Is Asked
This question tests understanding of order-statistics trees with duplicates and practical balanced BST design. It's a common systems programming interview topic that combines theoretical data structure knowledge with implementation considerations.

## Key Concepts
- **Augmented BST (treap)**: Each node maintains value, cnt, size, and priority fields
- **Duplicate handling**: Stored via cnt field; size stores the total count including duplicates in the subtree
- **Rank traversal**: Walks the tree, summing counts from left subtrees and comparing with target value
- **Select traversal**: Uses subtree sizes to navigate directly to the k-th element

## How Duplicates Are Stored
The cnt field at each node tracks how many times that value appears. When inserting a duplicate, we simply increment cnt rather than creating a new node. This keeps the tree balanced and efficient.

## How Select/Rank Traverse Equal Keys
- **rank(x)**: When traversing, if current node's value < x, add (left subtree size + cnt) to result and move right. Otherwise, move left. This counts all elements strictly less than x.
- **select(k)**: Navigate by comparing k with left subtree size. If k ≤ left size, go left. If k > left + cnt, subtract (left + cnt) and go right. Otherwise, we've found the node.

## Code Example
```javascript
class Node {
  constructor(v) {
    this.val = v;
    this.cnt = 1;
    this.size = 1;
    this.prio = Math.random();
    this.left = null;
    this.right = null;
  }
}

function update(n) {
  if (!n) return;
  n.size = n.cnt + (n.left?.size || 0) + (n.right?.size || 0);
}

function rank(root, x) {
  if (!root) return 0;
  if (x <= root.val) return rank(root.left, x);
  return (root.left?.size || 0) + root.cnt + rank(root.right, x);
}

function select(root, k) {
  if (!root) return null;
  const leftSize = root.left?.size || 0;
  if (k <= leftSize) return select(root.left, k);
  if (k > leftSize + root.cnt) return select(root.right, k - leftSize - root.cnt);
  return root.val;
}
```

