questions.answer:
Use blocks of size B ≈ √n. Each block stores a sorted values array and a frequency map (Map<number, count>). The append operation adds an element to the last block; if it becomes full, split it into two blocks. For insertAt and eraseAt, locate the target block, modify it, and rebuild its frequency map. For rangeFreq, iterate through blocks intersecting [l, r] and sum frequencies from each block's map for full blocks or scan values for partial blocks.

**Concrete example**: Start with [3, 5, 7] (one block of size 3).
- append(3): [3, 5, 7, 3] → block still fits, update frequency map: {3:2, 5:1, 7:1}
- insertAt(1, 4): [3, 4, 5, 7, 3] → shift elements, insert 4, rebuild map: {3:2, 4:1, 5:1, 7:1}
- eraseAt(2): [3, 4, 7, 3] → remove 5, rebuild map: {3:2, 4:1, 7:1}
- rangeFreq(1, 4, 3): indices 1-4 contain [4, 7, 3, ?] after eraseAt, array is [3, 4, 7, 3] so indices 1-4 = [4, 7, 3] → count of 3 = 1

questions.explanation:
## Why This Is Asked
This problem evaluates the ability to design a practical dynamic sequence with non-trivial frequency queries—a common requirement in analytics and data processing systems.

## Key Concepts
- **Sqrt decomposition** for dynamic sequences partitions data into blocks of approximately √n elements
- **Per-block frequency maps** enable O(√n) rangeFreq queries
- **Block maintenance**: splits when blocks overflow and merges when they underflow to maintain balance
- **Edge handling**: properly handles partial blocks during queries and updates

## Code Example
```javascript
class Block {
  constructor() {
    this.values = [];
    this.freq = new Map();
  }

  rebuild() {
    this.freq.clear();
    for (const v of this.values) {
      this.freq.set(v, (this.freq.get(v) || 0) + 1);
    }
  }
}

class DynamicSequence {
  constructor() {
    this.blocks = [];
    this.B = Math.ceil(Math.sqrt(10));
  }

  locate(index) {
    let offset = 0;
    for (const block of this.blocks) {
      if (offset + block.values.length > index) {
        return { block, pos: index - offset };
      }
      offset += block.values.length;
    }
  }

  append(value) {
    if (this.blocks.length === 0) this.blocks.push(new Block());
    const last = this.blocks[this.blocks.length - 1];
    last.values.push(value);
    last.freq.set(value, (last.freq.get(value) || 0) + 1);
    if (last.values.length > 2 * this.B) this.split(last);
  }

  split(block) {
    const mid = Math.floor(block.values.length / 2);
    const newBlock = new Block();
    newBlock.values = block.values.splice(mid);
    block.rebuild();
    newBlock.rebuild();
    this.blocks.push(newBlock);
  }

  rangeFreq(l, r, value) {
    let count = 0;
    const { block: startBlock, pos: startPos } = this.locate(l);
    const { block: endBlock, pos: endPos } = this.locate(r);

    if (startBlock === endBlock) {
      for (let i = startPos; i <= endPos; i++) {
        if (startBlock.values[i] === value) count++;
      }
      return count;
    }

    for (let i = startPos; i < startBlock.values.length; i++) {
      if (startBlock.values[i] === value) count++;
    }
    for (const block of this.blocks) {
      if (block === startBlock || block === endBlock) continue;
      count += block.freq.get(value) || 0;
    }
    for (let i = 0; i <= endPos; i++) {
      if (endBlock.values[i] === value) count++;
    }
    return count;
  }
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
