## Why This Question Is Asked
This question tests understanding of stack augmentation, a practical pattern for maintaining auxiliary state. It demonstrates the ability to design data structures that support efficient queries while handling edge cases like duplicates and empty states.

## Key Concepts
- Two auxiliary stacks (minStack and maxStack) track running minima and maxima in sync with the main stack
- Each push/pop operation updates all three stacks atomically, preserving O(1) time complexity
- Duplicates are handled naturally since the min/max is recalculated at each step
- Empty stack edge cases must be handled (typically by checking stack length before accessing top)

## Code Example
```javascript
class MinMaxStack {
  constructor() {
    this.stack = [];
    this.minStack = [];
    this.maxStack = [];
  }

  push(x) {
    this.stack.push(x);
    this.minStack.push(
      this.minStack.length ? Math.min(x, this.minStack[this.minStack.length - 1]) : x
    );
    this.maxStack.push(
      this.maxStack.length ? Math.max(x, this.maxStack[this.maxStack.length - 1]) : x
    );
  }

  pop() {
    if (this.stack.length === 0) return undefined;
    this.minStack.pop();
    this.maxStack.pop();
    return this.stack.pop();
  }

  top() {
    return this.stack[this.stack.length - 1];
  }

  getMin() {
    return this.minStack[this.minStack.length - 1];
  }

  getMax() {
    return this.maxStack[this.maxStack.length - 1];
  }
}
```

