## Why This Is Asked

Autocomplete-like prefix queries with dynamic updates are common in databases and search systems. A Trie with counts cleanly supports insertions, deletions, and fast prefix queries, even with duplicates.

## Key Concepts

- Trie with per-node pass-through counts
- O(len(word)) insertion/erasure; O(len(prefix)) prefix queries
- Correct handling of duplicates via counts, not just terminal markers

## Code Example

```javascript
class TrieNode {
  constructor() {
    this.next = new Map();
    this.cnt = 0;
    this.end = false;
  }
}

class WordTrie {
  constructor() { this.root = new TrieNode(); }

  insertWord(word) {
    let node = this.root;
    for (let ch of word) {
      if (!node.next.has(ch)) node.next.set(ch, new TrieNode());
      node = node.next.get(ch);
      node.cnt++;
    }
    node.end = true;
  }

  eraseWord(word) {
    let node = this.root;
    for (let ch of word) {
      if (!node.next.has(ch)) return;
      node = node.next.get(ch);
      node.cnt--;
    }
    node.end = false;
  }

  countWordsWithPrefix(prefix) {
    let node = this.root;
    for (let ch of prefix) {
      if (!node.next.has(ch)) return 0;
      node = node.next.get(ch);
    }
    return node.cnt;
  }
}
```

## How It Works

- **insertWord**: Traverses/creates nodes for each character, incrementing the pass-through count at each node
- **eraseWord**: Traverses existing nodes, decrementing counts; nodes with zero count can be pruned
- **countWordsWithPrefix**: Traverses to the prefix node and returns its pass-through count, representing all words that pass through this prefix

The pass-through count at each node represents how many words in the trie have that prefix, enabling O(len(prefix)) prefix queries while maintaining O(len(word)) updates.

